04:43.978 --> 04:44.978
(INHALES DEEPLY)

04:57.968 --> 04:58.988
(EXHALES)

05:02.118 --> 05:03.088
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

05:13.938 --> 05:15.068
(FLIES BUZZING)

05:36.998 --> 05:38.008
(GROANS)

05:57.435 --> 05:59.355
- (KNOCKING ON DOOR)
- (GASPING)

06:05.375 --> 06:07.375
LYLE: My dear Miss Ives.
I know you're there.

06:08.485 --> 06:10.315
I shan't go away.

06:13.285 --> 06:14.395
- (CONTINUES KNOCKING)
- (BREATHING HEAVILY)

06:15.395 --> 06:17.405
LYLE: I am singularly
persistent, my dear.

06:18.465 --> 06:20.324
I shall stay here all day and

06:20.325 --> 06:23.375
bloody my poor knuckles in
the endeavor if necessary.

06:41.355 --> 06:42.375
(DOOR OPENING)

06:45.405 --> 06:47.285
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

06:54.365 --> 06:55.445
(LYLE CHUCKLING)

06:56.246 --> 06:58.186
I love what you've done with the place.

07:01.296 --> 07:03.215
Ah, you can hear the bells.

07:03.216 --> 07:05.216
They're tolling all over the city.

07:05.356 --> 07:08.276
A fitting tribute to our fallen hero.

07:11.196 --> 07:12.196
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

07:12.336 --> 07:15.216
Oh, you would not have
heard of it, I'll hazard.

07:18.256 --> 07:19.346
Tennyson has died.

07:21.226 --> 07:24.276
He who dined with Coleridge
and walked with Wordsworth,

07:25.226 --> 07:27.256
our great poetic link to ages gone...

07:29.336 --> 07:32.155
"I hold it true, whate'er befall;

07:32.156 --> 07:34.186
I feel it, when I sorrow most;

07:34.356 --> 07:37.216
'Tis better to have loved and lost,

07:38.216 --> 07:40.246
Than never to have loved at all."

07:43.336 --> 07:46.215
You've ignored my letters and cards.

07:46.216 --> 07:48.185
I should be capaciously insulted

07:48.186 --> 07:50.226
but for my understanding of your...

07:51.216 --> 07:52.286
unique nature.

07:56.226 --> 07:57.325
My dear, dear Miss Ives.

07:57.326 --> 08:00.245
My heart is saddened to see you in these

08:00.246 --> 08:02.265
lowered circumstances,

08:02.266 --> 08:05.126
amongst the spiders and flies.

08:06.296 --> 08:08.185
Shall we not at least try
to bring you back to

08:08.186 --> 08:10.146
the mammalian community?

08:16.146 --> 08:17.989
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

08:18.045 --> 08:20.045
There was a time in my life...

08:22.045 --> 08:27.065
when I fell into a state
of ennui beyond compare.

08:28.287 --> 08:31.327
I was quite divorced from the
man I was or wanted to be.

08:32.347 --> 08:34.207
But my...

08:34.366 --> 08:36.217
unique nature...

08:37.246 --> 08:41.147
left me feeling loathed and loathsome.

08:42.327 --> 08:47.177
And then I was introduced to
a woman who saved my life.

08:49.167 --> 08:51.276
A mental doctor of a sort.

08:51.277 --> 08:54.266
I was skeptical but the
proof is in the pudding,

08:54.267 --> 08:57.206
and here I sit before you...

08:57.207 --> 08:59.287
resplendently who I am,

09:00.307 --> 09:04.317
entirely because of her ministrations.

09:06.207 --> 09:09.337
I beg you to see her.

09:16.287 --> 09:21.297
Life, for all its anguish,
is ours, Miss Ives.

09:24.257 --> 09:26.177
It belongs to no other.

09:30.347 --> 09:33.246
I'll make you an
appointment, if I may and

09:33.247 --> 09:35.257
we shan't have another word about it.

09:37.157 --> 09:38.317
Though you might want to...

09:40.157 --> 09:41.337
you know, fix up your hair.

09:51.257 --> 09:53.207
(LYLE BREATHES DEEPLY)

10:18.267 --> 10:19.287
(TRAIN HONKING)

10:24.307 --> 10:27.186
I've never seen so much nothing.

10:27.187 --> 10:28.277
Look closer.

10:30.247 --> 10:32.197
Recognize the patterns of nature.

10:33.217 --> 10:35.287
Snake holes. Wolf dens.

10:37.187 --> 10:39.157
And the animal bones.

10:40.307 --> 10:44.317
This whole country is
built on skeletons.

10:46.317 --> 10:48.337
One would like a cup of tea, though.

10:50.277 --> 10:52.236
Is there a club car, Marshal?

10:52.237 --> 10:53.317
In the back.

10:58.147 --> 11:00.157
You will excuse us, Mr. Talbot?

11:19.307 --> 11:20.337
(MAN COUGHING)

11:37.177 --> 11:38.327
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

11:47.367 --> 11:48.327
(MAN COUGHING)

12:14.147 --> 12:15.256
Do you have tea?

12:15.257 --> 12:16.277
I do.

12:17.297 --> 12:18.337
Two, please.

12:22.167 --> 12:23.297
You with that prisoner back there?

12:24.247 --> 12:25.296
Yes.

12:25.297 --> 12:26.316
You're British, though.

12:26.317 --> 12:28.296
We are extraditing him to stand trial.

12:28.297 --> 12:30.206
Ah, he doesn't look so dangerous to me.

12:30.207 --> 12:31.226
What'd he do?

12:31.227 --> 12:33.346
He butchered a lot of people

12:33.347 --> 12:35.347
and ate a fair number of them.

13:01.157 --> 13:02.247
(SNORING)

13:17.347 --> 13:19.197
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

13:25.177 --> 13:26.236
Hey!

13:26.237 --> 13:28.156
Hey, you can't go up there!

13:28.157 --> 13:28.603
(GASPS)

13:31.357 --> 13:32.357
(COCKS GUN)

13:34.357 --> 13:36.137
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

13:43.357 --> 13:44.327
(INDISTINCT YELLING)

13:47.187 --> 13:48.217
- (GUNFIRE)
- (GROANS)

13:54.207 --> 13:55.247
(SHUDDERING)

13:56.287 --> 13:57.257
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

14:06.347 --> 14:08.226
MAN: Please, no.

14:08.227 --> 14:09.267
No! Ah.

14:10.257 --> 14:11.237
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

14:11.238 --> 14:12.366
Please, sir.

14:12.367 --> 14:15.176
You would not harm a defenseless female?

14:15.177 --> 14:16.186
(DOOR OPENS)

14:16.187 --> 14:17.167
- (GUNFIRE)
- (GROANS)

14:29.157 --> 14:30.347
Welcome home, Ethan.

14:38.147 --> 14:39.196
Hyah.

14:39.197 --> 14:40.237
(HORSES WHINNYING)

14:52.317 --> 14:54.227
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

15:13.307 --> 15:15.147
(MUEZZIN CALLING TO PRAYER)

15:22.147 --> 15:24.347
SIR MALCOLM: <i>Sixth of October, 1892.</i>

15:25.277 --> 15:27.147
<i>My dear Vanessa.</i>

15:28.337 --> 15:30.356
<i>- So it's done.</i>
- (INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

15:30.357 --> 15:33.146
<i>I've buried our friend
Sembene in the mountains</i>

15:33.147 --> 15:34.306
<i>from whence he came.</i>

15:34.307 --> 15:38.167
<i>It was a private ceremony
with no ornamentation.</i>

15:39.327 --> 15:41.316
<i>Most of the local natives
have been run off</i>

15:41.317 --> 15:43.346
<i>or captured by the Germans
and the Belgians,</i>

15:43.347 --> 15:45.316
<i>for the rubber and ivory trade.</i>

15:45.317 --> 15:48.357
<i>For slaves in all but name.</i>

15:50.287 --> 15:53.326
<i>What romance I saw in
Africa is done for me.</i>

15:53.327 --> 15:56.316
<i>The land is tainted now, beyond repair</i>

15:56.317 --> 15:59.267
<i>and I want to be quit
of the filthy place.</i>

16:01.147 --> 16:02.216
<i>What then?</i>

16:02.217 --> 16:03.276
(SIGHS)

16:03.277 --> 16:05.316
<i>Are there no fresh wonders left?</i>

16:05.317 --> 16:07.367
<i>No worlds yet to conquer?</i>

16:11.277 --> 16:14.156
<i>When I have my itinerary
in mind, I'll cable.</i>

16:14.157 --> 16:16.327
<i>I hope this finds you well and at peace,</i>

16:17.247 --> 16:19.237
<i>or such a peace as those
as we can summon.</i>

16:20.317 --> 16:24.157
<i>Yours sincerely, Malcolm Murray.</i>

16:30.277 --> 16:32.137
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

16:46.207 --> 16:48.346
Sir, money for my baby.

16:48.347 --> 16:50.147
Money. Yes.

16:51.207 --> 16:53.087
- SIR MALCOLM: Here.
- WOMAN: More!

16:53.211 --> 16:54.539
You're a rich Briton.

16:54.700 --> 16:57.256
Come with me. I let you fuck me.

16:57.257 --> 16:58.336
Any way you want, John Bull.

16:58.337 --> 17:00.187
No. Sorry.

17:04.207 --> 17:06.307
Maybe I let them fuck you, John Bull!

17:07.166 --> 17:08.186
Ah!

17:08.327 --> 17:10.227
(MEN CLAMORING)

17:11.327 --> 17:13.207
(GRUNTING)

17:42.257 --> 17:43.297
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

17:56.367 --> 17:58.177
(MAN GROANS SOFTLY)

18:03.197 --> 18:06.157
Old traditions die hard,
don't they, Sir Malcolm?

18:07.207 --> 18:08.287
(WIND HOWLING)

18:10.297 --> 18:12.167
(BOAT CREAKING)

18:28.227 --> 18:29.306
(MEN SHUDDERING)

18:29.307 --> 18:31.237
(MEN COUGHING)

18:41.327 --> 18:43.306
DOCTOR: It's an unholy thing,

18:43.307 --> 18:45.157
eating human flesh.

18:47.317 --> 18:49.186
Better to starve.

18:49.187 --> 18:50.217
SAILOR: I'll not starve.

18:51.227 --> 18:53.226
We've eaten the goddamn leather...

18:53.227 --> 18:54.337
and the fucking wood

18:55.357 --> 18:57.237
and every goddamn rat and bug.

18:58.237 --> 19:00.277
There's nothing left but them on deck.

19:01.277 --> 19:03.306
So I say we eat.

19:03.307 --> 19:04.297
Better to die.

19:04.298 --> 19:06.197
(RUMBLING)

19:12.277 --> 19:13.356
We draw lots.

19:13.357 --> 19:16.176
So eke out a few more
days and then what?

19:16.177 --> 19:18.166
If we're gonna die, let us die as men,

19:18.167 --> 19:19.246
not animals.

19:19.247 --> 19:20.237
(SCOFFS)

19:24.267 --> 19:25.297
That amuses you?

19:26.317 --> 19:28.177
(BOY COUGHING)

19:38.357 --> 19:40.167
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

19:47.227 --> 19:49.167
He's not long for it.

19:58.297 --> 20:00.147
Hasten the end...

20:02.187 --> 20:03.327
and let us eat then.

20:09.177 --> 20:11.227
(SHUDDERING) You want him to suffer?

20:12.257 --> 20:14.337
Let us put him out of
it, you cruel bastard.

20:16.337 --> 20:17.356
Let us eat!

20:17.357 --> 20:19.237
(BOY WHEEZING)

20:34.367 --> 20:36.217
(CREATURE SHUSHING)

20:44.257 --> 20:45.307
(VOCALIZING)

20:55.357 --> 21:00.227
<i>♪ Guardian angels God will send thee ♪</i>

21:02.207 --> 21:06.247
<i>♪ All through the night ♪</i>

21:10.237 --> 21:15.247
<i>♪ Soft the drowsy hours Are creeping ♪</i>

21:16.247 --> 21:21.227
<i>♪ Hill and dale In slumber sleeping ♪</i>

21:22.187 --> 21:26.357
<i>♪ I my loved ones' Watch am keeping ♪</i>

21:27.327 --> 21:31.307
<i>♪ All through the night ♪</i>

21:36.257 --> 21:37.217
(GASPS)

21:39.137 --> 21:40.237
(BOY CONTINUES WHEEZING)

21:44.207 --> 21:45.287
(SHUDDERING)

21:47.357 --> 21:48.366
How long does he have?

21:48.367 --> 21:51.137
A few days. Less.

21:52.317 --> 21:54.156
They won't give him that.

21:54.157 --> 21:55.337
Better he die quickly.

21:58.247 --> 21:59.346
(BONE CRACKING)

21:59.347 --> 22:01.167
(WHIMPERING)

22:04.287 --> 22:05.287
I wish you luck.

22:06.327 --> 22:07.297
Where are you going?

22:08.207 --> 22:09.257
Home.

22:49.187 --> 22:51.167
I don't drink spirits.

22:52.207 --> 22:53.247
As you like.

22:55.337 --> 22:57.246
American Indian?

22:57.247 --> 23:00.147
Chiricahua Apache by birth and right.

23:00.367 --> 23:02.277
Are you familiar with the West?

23:03.217 --> 23:05.136
Only through the newspapers.

23:05.137 --> 23:06.267
It is not what it was.

23:07.267 --> 23:10.277
But then what is, Sir Malcolm?

23:12.137 --> 23:13.227
How do you know me?

23:14.157 --> 23:15.366
I've been following you.

23:15.367 --> 23:17.146
In Africa?

23:17.147 --> 23:19.367
I missed you in London,
so I came to this place.

23:20.287 --> 23:23.277
I waited for your return
from the Interior.

23:24.207 --> 23:25.316
How'd you know I'd return?

23:25.317 --> 23:29.176
Because you can't die until
you've served your purpose.

23:29.177 --> 23:30.257
And what's that?

23:32.207 --> 23:35.156
To fight the great
demons of earth and sky

23:35.157 --> 23:36.357
until you are dead.

23:38.147 --> 23:40.156
I'm done with that.

23:40.157 --> 23:42.247
Better say you're done with breathing.

23:45.137 --> 23:46.146
You must come with me.

23:46.147 --> 23:48.226
- Where?
- America.

23:48.227 --> 23:49.247
(CHUCKLES)

23:51.177 --> 23:54.267
Ethan Chandler needs your help.

23:56.277 --> 23:58.307
And you expect me to come
with you to America?

23:59.227 --> 24:00.287
I demand it.

24:03.137 --> 24:05.196
My name is Kaetenay.

24:05.197 --> 24:07.256
Come with me and I'll
tell you the story.

24:07.257 --> 24:08.306
To where?

24:08.307 --> 24:10.267
The New Mexico Territory.

24:11.177 --> 24:13.277
My home... and his home.

24:14.327 --> 24:17.287
He who is almost my son.

24:22.137 --> 24:24.277
You know you have a further destiny.

24:25.237 --> 24:27.197
Let this be it.

24:31.157 --> 24:33.157
Our son needs us.

24:37.197 --> 24:40.137
Where is your heart, Malcolm Murray?

24:40.357 --> 24:43.277
Be who you are.

24:46.327 --> 24:48.197
(SIGHS)

24:53.327 --> 24:55.217
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

25:00.167 --> 25:01.217
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

25:06.357 --> 25:08.137
Mr. Talbot.

25:13.307 --> 25:16.217
- Who are you?
- Hell, we're your liberators.

25:17.167 --> 25:18.256
From those Federals who
would have hung you

25:18.257 --> 25:20.236
from the neck until dead,
as the warrant goes.

25:20.237 --> 25:22.167
You work for my father.

25:25.157 --> 25:26.356
He killed all those people on that train

25:26.357 --> 25:28.207
just to get to me.

25:29.247 --> 25:30.337
Man wants to see you again.

25:32.167 --> 25:34.267
Well, maybe it's about time he did.

25:42.207 --> 25:43.287
(EXHALES)

25:45.267 --> 25:47.297
Cheer up, Ethan. We're taking you home.

25:50.257 --> 25:51.317
Good luck.

26:00.297 --> 26:01.337
(INDISTINCT YELLING)

26:04.147 --> 26:05.237
(STEAMERS HONKING)

26:13.337 --> 26:15.277
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

26:24.257 --> 26:26.256
MAN 1: Look at this black bastard!

26:26.257 --> 26:27.266
MAN 2: Not from around here, is he?

26:27.267 --> 26:29.147
MAN 1: Go home, you dirty wog!

26:46.307 --> 26:48.346
Don't need no bloody niggers here.

26:48.347 --> 26:53.237
Back to fucking Calcutta with
every one of you, say I.

27:21.277 --> 27:22.297
Victor!

27:26.167 --> 27:27.137
(KNOCKING)

27:29.307 --> 27:30.337
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

27:31.237 --> 27:33.197
Dr. Frankenstein.

27:35.217 --> 27:36.337
Dr. Jekyll.

27:56.267 --> 27:57.367
FRANKENSTEIN: Thank you for coming.

27:59.137 --> 28:00.347
I had no one else, you see.

28:03.167 --> 28:04.226
No one.

28:04.227 --> 28:07.276
Is it love or work?

28:07.277 --> 28:08.347
(CHUCKLES)

28:09.367 --> 28:11.227
Both.

28:17.167 --> 28:18.167
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

28:21.267 --> 28:22.337
(FRANKENSTEIN SHUDDERING)

28:25.357 --> 28:29.176
Love, work, and narcotics.

28:29.177 --> 28:30.327
Where do we begin, Victor?

28:39.227 --> 28:40.347
There is much I...

28:44.297 --> 28:47.357
I have been working.

28:50.207 --> 28:52.157
That is the root of it.

28:55.217 --> 28:57.177
The old work?

28:59.177 --> 29:00.217
Yes.

29:01.287 --> 29:03.147
And?

29:05.357 --> 29:07.177
Success.

29:14.267 --> 29:16.216
When we were in school we dreamed,

29:16.217 --> 29:17.226
you remember,

29:17.227 --> 29:19.136
of walking into the
Royal Society together

29:19.137 --> 29:20.186
with our triumph

29:20.187 --> 29:22.317
of presenting our evidence
with a glorious flourish.

29:24.307 --> 29:26.166
And how all those who had hated us,

29:26.167 --> 29:29.187
and laughed at us, would be silenced.

29:30.227 --> 29:33.186
And we, heroes both,

29:33.187 --> 29:36.187
would conquer the world
and beat back death.

29:37.337 --> 29:39.267
I have conquered death.

29:43.227 --> 29:44.367
And have created monsters.

29:46.277 --> 29:49.197
None more so than the man
who sits before you.

29:52.297 --> 29:54.277
I've told no one this.

29:58.277 --> 30:00.197
I am your true friend.

30:02.257 --> 30:06.257
Then, now, and always.

30:10.267 --> 30:15.237
Then I'll unfold a tale better
suited to black midnight.

30:20.197 --> 30:23.207
(SNIFFLES) When I left
school, I came to London.

30:24.267 --> 30:27.247
I found work at a
resurrectionist's mortuary.

30:29.357 --> 30:30.347
(SLURPS)

30:31.357 --> 30:35.346
Thus the tools of my sorry
trade were all around me.

30:35.347 --> 30:39.326
And before long, my mind
turned fully to re-animation

30:39.327 --> 30:42.326
and bringing those sorry lumps
of flesh to renewed life.

30:42.327 --> 30:44.217
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

30:47.227 --> 30:48.297
(BELL TOLLING)

30:54.147 --> 30:54.634
(GASPING)

31:12.237 --> 31:13.287
(INHALES DEEPLY)

31:27.327 --> 31:30.136
Good afternoon. May I help you?

31:30.137 --> 31:31.207
(WHISPERING) Yes.

31:32.147 --> 31:34.357
Yes, I'm here to see Dr. Seward.

31:37.147 --> 31:38.306
Oh, I see.

31:38.307 --> 31:40.297
- Have you an appointment?
- Yes.

31:41.297 --> 31:43.306
My name is Vanessa Ives.

31:43.307 --> 31:46.216
I was referred by a friend.

31:46.217 --> 31:48.216
He said I ought to come.

31:48.217 --> 31:49.326
Oh, lovely.

31:49.327 --> 31:51.266
Yes. Well, do sit down.

31:51.267 --> 31:53.137
Be back in two shakes.

32:03.217 --> 32:04.247
(CLOCK TICKING)

32:11.147 --> 32:12.147
(DOOR OPENING)

32:12.148 --> 32:13.287
SECRETARY: This way, Miss Ives.

32:15.307 --> 32:17.237
Make yourself at home, please.

32:22.197 --> 32:23.357
DR. SEWARD: I'll be
with you in a second.

32:25.347 --> 32:27.167
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

32:30.297 --> 32:31.357
Take a seat, Miss Ives.

32:37.277 --> 32:39.197
I said, sit down, Miss Ives.

32:43.147 --> 32:44.346
Since I'm sure you're not
familiar with alienism,

32:44.347 --> 32:46.206
I'll tell you how it works.

32:46.207 --> 32:49.226
If I accept your case, I
insist on one-hour sessions

32:49.227 --> 32:51.266
every other day, no exceptions.

32:51.267 --> 32:53.346
Our sessions are strictly confidential.

32:53.347 --> 32:55.246
I don't talk about them and you can't.

32:55.247 --> 32:57.196
No exceptions.

32:57.197 --> 32:59.186
Given we are a new branch of science,

32:59.187 --> 33:01.136
there's no standard scale for fees,

33:01.137 --> 33:03.216
so I charge 10 shillings per session.

33:03.217 --> 33:06.156
As much as a visit to a
halfway-decent dentist.

33:06.157 --> 33:08.296
So you can come see me
or get your teeth fixed.

33:08.297 --> 33:09.337
Your choice.

33:10.317 --> 33:12.177
Why are you scratching your hand?

33:13.297 --> 33:14.367
Why were you doing that?

33:18.207 --> 33:19.276
I had an itch.

33:19.277 --> 33:21.167
No, you didn't.

33:24.267 --> 33:26.286
This is a challenge.

33:26.287 --> 33:28.317
You're seeing if I'm worthy of study.

33:29.287 --> 33:32.266
This is a preliminary
consultation, Miss Ives.

33:32.267 --> 33:34.177
Please call me Vanessa.

33:35.297 --> 33:37.276
I'm not your friend, or your priest,

33:37.277 --> 33:38.296
or your husband.

33:38.297 --> 33:40.166
I'm your doctor.

33:40.167 --> 33:42.246
You come to me to get
better because you are ill,

33:42.247 --> 33:43.286
no other reason.

33:43.287 --> 33:45.167
Do you understand that?

33:45.327 --> 33:48.156
- No exceptions.
- Yes.

33:48.157 --> 33:49.336
Do you understand that you are ill?

33:49.337 --> 33:52.276
Not bad, not unworthy, just ill.

33:52.277 --> 33:54.206
Do you understand that?

33:54.207 --> 33:55.296
Yes.

33:55.297 --> 33:56.326
Are your hands dry?

33:56.327 --> 33:58.206
- Yes.
- Then perhaps you should

33:58.207 --> 33:59.246
invest in some hand cream

33:59.247 --> 34:01.327
and save yourself the
expense of seeing me.

34:02.267 --> 34:03.336
I have money.

34:03.337 --> 34:05.207
You mean your husband has money.

34:05.307 --> 34:07.326
I have no husband.

34:07.327 --> 34:09.235
I have family money.

34:09.237 --> 34:10.335
A small inheritance.

34:10.337 --> 34:13.206
Small or large, really?

34:13.206 --> 34:15.136
Large.

34:15.137 --> 34:16.266
My late father was a solicitor.

34:16.266 --> 34:18.177
Then why did you say small?

34:21.137 --> 34:22.295
I don't know.

34:22.297 --> 34:23.335
Politeness, I suppose.

34:23.337 --> 34:25.216
Is it impolite to have money?

34:25.217 --> 34:26.295
I don't know!

34:26.297 --> 34:28.216
DR. SEWARD: I don't
care about politeness.

34:28.217 --> 34:29.366
There are no manners here.

34:29.367 --> 34:32.216
If you want to scream like
an animal, you should.

34:32.217 --> 34:33.306
Or cry. Or yell.

34:34.137 --> 34:37.136
There are no emotions
unwelcome in this room,

34:37.137 --> 34:38.286
and if this process
doesn't appeal to you,

34:38.286 --> 34:40.137
the door is there.

34:46.147 --> 34:47.347
You don't want me to leave.

34:48.266 --> 34:49.335
Why not?

34:49.337 --> 34:52.295
Because I scratch my hand.

34:52.297 --> 34:53.326
You find that telling.

34:53.327 --> 34:54.335
Of what?

34:54.337 --> 34:56.347
Those phobias that interest you.

34:58.157 --> 34:59.247
Do you interest me?

35:00.227 --> 35:01.187
I might.

35:01.317 --> 35:03.266
You're not sure.

35:03.267 --> 35:05.166
You don't need the 10 shillings.

35:05.167 --> 35:07.187
But you do need interesting people.

35:08.187 --> 35:09.187
Why?

35:09.188 --> 35:10.316
- To collect.
- To cure.

35:10.317 --> 35:12.157
Is there a difference?

35:22.167 --> 35:23.256
We've met before.

35:23.257 --> 35:25.166
DR. SEWARD: I'm sure not.

35:25.167 --> 35:28.357
I mean, I've known
someone very like you.

35:29.317 --> 35:32.167
Joan Clayton was her name.

35:33.197 --> 35:35.196
My family name is Clayton.

35:35.197 --> 35:36.226
Devon people.

35:36.227 --> 35:37.276
From the West Country.

35:37.277 --> 35:39.266
My ancestors...

35:39.267 --> 35:40.346
Yes.

35:40.347 --> 35:42.207
Generations ago.

35:43.147 --> 35:44.236
But that's immaterial.

35:44.237 --> 35:46.316
I'm your doctor, nothing
more, understood?

35:46.317 --> 35:48.136
Come tomorrow at 10:00 a.m.

35:48.137 --> 35:50.197
And every other day at the same time.

35:53.167 --> 35:55.237
We'll begin our sessions?
We already have.

35:57.177 --> 35:58.356
But... (SCRIBBLING)

35:58.357 --> 36:01.146
but, don't you want to
know what's wrong with me?

36:01.147 --> 36:02.326
I already know what's wrong with you.

36:02.327 --> 36:04.226
You're unhappy.

36:04.227 --> 36:06.196
You're isolated.

36:06.197 --> 36:08.166
You think you're the cause
of this unhappiness

36:08.167 --> 36:11.206
and are unworthy of affection
so you've few friends.

36:11.207 --> 36:14.236
Recently you lost something
you think very important.

36:14.237 --> 36:17.316
Your lover, your faith,
your family, or all three.

36:17.317 --> 36:18.326
You blame yourself for this,

36:18.327 --> 36:20.296
so it makes you neurotic,
and you don't sleep

36:20.297 --> 36:23.206
and don't eat anything healthy anyway.

36:23.207 --> 36:24.276
You used to take care
of your appearance,

36:24.277 --> 36:27.356
but you've lost interest in
that, so you avoid mirrors.

36:27.357 --> 36:30.196
Sunlight bothers you,
so you avoid that too,

36:30.197 --> 36:31.246
about which you're guilty

36:31.247 --> 36:32.286
because you think it's unhealthy

36:32.287 --> 36:34.296
and even immoral not to like the sun.

36:34.297 --> 36:36.246
You're not a woman of convention

36:36.247 --> 36:38.246
or you wouldn't be here, but
you like to pretend you are

36:38.247 --> 36:39.811
so people don't notice you.

36:40.147 --> 36:41.326
But you sometimes like that as well,

36:41.327 --> 36:43.186
and can dress to draw the eye.

36:43.187 --> 36:45.246
But then you think the men
who look at you are fools,

36:45.247 --> 36:48.326
or worse, to be taken in by
such an obvious outward show.

36:48.327 --> 36:51.346
So, instead you're drawn
to dark, complicated,

36:51.347 --> 36:53.236
impossible men,

36:53.237 --> 36:56.156
assuring your own unhappiness
and isolation because,

36:56.157 --> 36:58.277
after all, you're happiest alone.

36:59.177 --> 37:01.176
But not even then because you can't

37:01.177 --> 37:03.136
stop thinking about what you've lost,

37:03.137 --> 37:05.256
again, for which you blame yourself.

37:05.257 --> 37:06.356
So the cycle goes on,

37:06.357 --> 37:09.237
the snake eating its own tail.

37:11.227 --> 37:14.227
Or you can just have your teeth fixed.

37:16.287 --> 37:18.136
I'll come tomorrow.

37:18.137 --> 37:19.317
First, you've something to do.

37:21.177 --> 37:23.226
Break the cycle for this one day.

37:23.227 --> 37:25.286
Do something you've never done before.

37:25.287 --> 37:26.326
Right now.

37:26.327 --> 37:27.366
Doesn't matter what it is.

37:27.367 --> 37:29.286
Eat something new.

37:29.287 --> 37:31.177
Go somewhere different.

37:31.327 --> 37:33.206
Tell me about it tomorrow.

37:33.207 --> 37:34.336
You understand?

37:34.337 --> 37:36.186
Yes.

37:36.187 --> 37:37.327
Pay my secretary on the way out.

37:38.337 --> 37:39.327
Thank you.

37:43.247 --> 37:45.317
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

37:53.137 --> 37:54.237
(FRANKENSTEIN PANTING)

37:54.357 --> 37:56.197
The house of pain.

37:57.347 --> 37:59.187
In all its glory.

38:07.217 --> 38:09.247
DR. JEKYLL: So this is
where your Lily was born.

38:26.367 --> 38:28.197
What a thing, Victor.

38:29.227 --> 38:31.237
To have created life.

38:33.267 --> 38:34.306
Such a miracle.

38:34.307 --> 38:37.177
Yes, my miracle.

38:38.237 --> 38:39.337
Bringing forth horrors.

38:40.217 --> 38:43.137
And every act of my hideous creations,

38:44.177 --> 38:46.356
their every sin, hangs on me.

38:46.357 --> 38:48.306
You wonder why I turn to the needle.

38:48.307 --> 38:49.366
'Twas that or the noose.

38:49.367 --> 38:51.196
You're no suicide.

38:51.197 --> 38:52.236
You think too much of yourself.

38:52.237 --> 38:53.316
Ah, well, if that's what you...

38:53.317 --> 38:56.326
I haven't heard a bloody peep
from you in over five years,

38:56.327 --> 38:58.346
which caused me no small amount of pain,

38:58.347 --> 39:00.256
while we're at it,

39:00.257 --> 39:02.286
as I was never precisely
abundant with friends,

39:02.287 --> 39:04.136
if you remember.

39:04.137 --> 39:07.336
And now you call me here
and tell me all this,

39:07.337 --> 39:12.227
all these dreadful, gorgeous secrets.

39:13.327 --> 39:14.327
Why?

39:14.328 --> 39:15.366
I need your skills.

39:15.367 --> 39:17.246
You need my friendship first, Victor.
Look at you.

39:17.247 --> 39:19.247
That doesn't matter, don't you see?

39:20.287 --> 39:23.247
Only the evil I have spawned matters.

39:26.327 --> 39:28.227
You must help me destroy her.

39:32.167 --> 39:33.346
You want me to help you kill Lily?

39:33.347 --> 39:35.326
Yes. You will do that.

39:35.327 --> 39:37.137
You will help me.

39:37.237 --> 39:39.216
I have no one else.

39:39.217 --> 39:40.346
I am not a killer.

39:40.347 --> 39:42.137
Are you not?

39:43.267 --> 39:46.156
That despised half-caste boy I knew,

39:46.157 --> 39:47.176
crying himself to sleep.

39:47.177 --> 39:48.236
That shunned little wog

39:48.237 --> 39:50.256
who had not a friend in
the world aside from me.

39:50.257 --> 39:51.296
He could kill.

39:51.297 --> 39:53.206
God, he wanted to.

39:53.207 --> 39:55.236
You remember late at night in
our room, over the hookah,

39:55.237 --> 39:57.296
listing the names of all the
boys who had insulted you?

39:57.297 --> 40:00.136
The recitation of your
potential victims.

40:00.137 --> 40:01.257
Your nightly prayers.

40:02.347 --> 40:04.267
That anger inside you,

40:04.357 --> 40:06.226
all that rage.

40:06.227 --> 40:07.256
Have you lost it?

40:07.257 --> 40:09.177
I have learned to control it.

40:12.197 --> 40:15.246
That is the essence of my work now.

40:15.247 --> 40:18.177
The neurologic chemical
reactions of the brain.

40:19.297 --> 40:22.217
Taming the beast within.

40:23.197 --> 40:25.156
You were the most brilliant
chemist I ever knew...

40:25.157 --> 40:26.157
Don't flatter me.

40:26.158 --> 40:27.247
I know what I am.

40:28.227 --> 40:30.227
And you're right to acknowledge it.

40:32.267 --> 40:34.287
But I know you better
than you think, old man.

40:35.347 --> 40:39.247
The lonely boy I met at school
was, above all, romantic.

40:40.307 --> 40:42.366
His heart stirred to poetry

40:42.367 --> 40:45.197
even more than anatomy and Galvanism.

40:46.347 --> 40:48.226
You're still that boy, Victor.

40:48.227 --> 40:51.317
Be honest with yourself and with me.

40:53.187 --> 40:57.267
You don't want to kill Lily,
you want to love her.

40:58.207 --> 40:59.266
(CHUCKLES)

40:59.267 --> 41:00.276
That's impossible.

41:00.277 --> 41:03.257
You have no idea of the
depths of her depravity.

41:05.247 --> 41:07.207
What if I could make her as she was?

41:07.277 --> 41:09.286
Before she turned on you?

41:09.287 --> 41:11.197
Before her evil emerged?

41:12.157 --> 41:13.237
What then?

41:15.197 --> 41:18.157
What if I could tame her?

41:19.267 --> 41:20.367
Domesticate her.

41:22.227 --> 41:25.277
Leave her purring like
a kitten on your lap.

41:26.327 --> 41:27.357
What then?

41:29.217 --> 41:30.277
Would you want that?

41:35.167 --> 41:36.206
Can you?

41:36.207 --> 41:37.237
Answer me.

41:37.337 --> 41:39.136
Yes.

41:39.137 --> 41:40.297
Then shall we attempt it?

41:41.347 --> 41:43.247
You and I, brother?

41:45.247 --> 41:46.267
Yes.

41:50.367 --> 41:52.227
I have to go to work now.

41:53.197 --> 41:56.137
But on Saturday I will take
you to my humble laboratory

41:57.207 --> 42:00.226
and you can witness my miracles.

42:00.227 --> 42:01.287
But hear me.

42:02.197 --> 42:04.136
If we should fail,

42:04.137 --> 42:06.296
if we prove incapable of helping her,

42:06.297 --> 42:08.137
we destroy her.

42:08.367 --> 42:10.217
Utterly.

42:11.337 --> 42:14.207
So it will be as if she
never walked this earth.

42:19.137 --> 42:19.572
(EXHALES)

42:24.327 --> 42:26.217
(INHALES SHARPLY)

42:27.277 --> 42:28.297
(EXHALES)

42:54.227 --> 42:55.337
Death ribbon, ma'am?

42:57.197 --> 42:59.176
What? Sorry?

42:59.177 --> 43:00.346
Death ribbon, ma'am.

43:00.347 --> 43:02.176
For the poet.

43:02.177 --> 43:03.226
The dead poet like.

43:03.227 --> 43:05.246
Penny apiece, honor Mr. Tennyson?

43:05.247 --> 43:06.287
Yes, all right.

43:08.337 --> 43:10.326
You're looking at my face.

43:10.327 --> 43:11.287
Its paleness.

43:12.307 --> 43:14.266
They call it the anemia.

43:14.267 --> 43:16.316
Something to do with my blood...

43:16.317 --> 43:18.187
my blood.

43:19.367 --> 43:21.167
Thank you.

43:22.267 --> 43:27.207
Savor this day, my beautiful
lady, my beloved.

43:33.267 --> 43:34.307
(BELL TOLLING)

45:05.347 --> 45:08.137
MAN: The small ones are
the most dangerous.

45:08.267 --> 45:10.186
<i>Leiurus quinquestraitus.</i>

45:10.187 --> 45:12.266
There, in the center, the albino one.

45:12.267 --> 45:14.326
Also known as the Omdurman scorpion

45:14.327 --> 45:16.347
or, more colloquially,
as the "Deathstalker."

45:17.297 --> 45:20.266
Albinoism is exceedingly rare in nature,

45:20.267 --> 45:22.216
a sign of caution to the world.

45:22.217 --> 45:23.286
The absence of color, that is...

45:23.287 --> 45:25.206
signifying what?

45:25.207 --> 45:26.346
Bloodlessness. Uniqueness.

45:26.347 --> 45:28.157
(SOFTLY) Beware.

45:31.317 --> 45:33.336
He's from the Sudan. I think it's a he.

45:33.337 --> 45:34.356
It's very hard to sex them

45:34.357 --> 45:36.366
unless they're breeding, arachnids.

45:36.367 --> 45:38.366
You'd think this fellow would
be the most dangerous,

45:38.367 --> 45:40.347
with his enormous claws.

45:41.287 --> 45:42.356
Why do you think I'm interested

45:42.357 --> 45:44.226
in the dangerous ones?

45:44.227 --> 45:45.296
MAN: Everyone is.

45:45.297 --> 45:47.216
They imagine them crawling
over their bodies

45:47.217 --> 45:48.236
as they sleep.

45:48.237 --> 45:49.326
That's what draws most people in.

45:49.327 --> 45:51.256
The fear. You don't see them lining up

45:51.257 --> 45:54.206
to look at the sheep, more's
the pity, glorious animals.

45:54.207 --> 45:57.236
They love the tooth and
claw, the predators.

45:57.237 --> 45:59.166
Would you like to touch one?

45:59.167 --> 46:01.166
- A predator?
- A scorpion.

46:01.167 --> 46:02.306
I have.

46:02.307 --> 46:05.146
- You've touched a scorpion?
- Mmm-hmm.

46:05.147 --> 46:07.276
My God. Don't tell me
you're a zoologist.

46:07.277 --> 46:10.147
(CHUCKLING) No, but you are.

46:11.167 --> 46:12.316
Dr. Alexander Sweet, hello.

46:12.317 --> 46:14.296
I'm the boss here, more or less.

46:14.297 --> 46:16.256
Director of Zoological Studies.

46:16.257 --> 46:17.317
Noah in his ark.

46:18.257 --> 46:20.146
Vanessa Ives.

46:20.147 --> 46:22.346
But Noah's animals were living.

46:22.347 --> 46:26.357
Oh, I think of these ones
as alive, just quiet.

46:28.237 --> 46:29.347
Taxidermy!

46:30.227 --> 46:31.356
- What?
- Your hobby.

46:31.357 --> 46:34.156
That's where you touched a scorpion.

46:34.157 --> 46:35.216
No.

46:35.217 --> 46:37.197
Though I practiced it as a child.

46:38.157 --> 46:39.236
So did I.

46:39.237 --> 46:41.306
That's where I fell in
love with all this.

46:41.307 --> 46:44.256
A harmless hobby giving way to, what?

46:44.257 --> 46:46.287
A calling, I suppose.

46:47.357 --> 46:50.246
Did you know there are
certain deep-sea fish

46:50.247 --> 46:51.316
that create their own light

46:51.317 --> 46:54.316
and feed on lethal volcanic gasses?

46:54.317 --> 46:56.247
That's supposed to be impossible.

46:57.237 --> 47:00.366
And bats in Australia as large as dogs.

47:00.367 --> 47:03.316
And that American coyotes mate for life.

47:03.317 --> 47:06.146
And enormous octopi that
can squeeze their bodies

47:06.147 --> 47:08.297
through holes no larger
than a ha'penny coin.

47:09.267 --> 47:11.237
Can you imagine that?

47:12.347 --> 47:17.167
If only we would stop
and look and wonder.

47:19.147 --> 47:20.207
And wonder.

47:21.287 --> 47:23.336
Do you have a favorite?

47:23.337 --> 47:25.296
Not meant to.

47:25.297 --> 47:28.166
But mostly the unloved ones.

47:28.167 --> 47:29.356
The unvisited ones.

47:29.357 --> 47:32.227
The cases that get dusty and ignored.

47:33.247 --> 47:35.347
All the broken and shunned creatures.

47:38.327 --> 47:40.366
Someone's got to care for them.

47:40.367 --> 47:42.327
Who shall it be if not us?

47:46.357 --> 47:47.337
Yes.

47:48.307 --> 47:50.147
(FOOTSTEPS)

47:51.307 --> 47:53.316
Dr. Sweet, may I have a moment?

47:53.317 --> 47:54.366
Of course.

47:54.367 --> 47:57.247
Mr. Dudman, may I present to you Miss...

47:59.317 --> 48:01.246
I'm sorry, I've forgotten your name.

48:01.247 --> 48:03.297
Vanessa Ives. Hello.

48:04.267 --> 48:05.296
In the lab, sir.

48:05.297 --> 48:07.256
I have a question about the tiger.

48:07.257 --> 48:08.297
If you'll excuse me?

48:09.177 --> 48:12.157
Far be it from me to get
between a man and his tiger.

48:12.297 --> 48:14.156
Thank you, Miss Ives.

48:14.157 --> 48:15.346
I do hope you'll enjoy the exhibits.

48:15.347 --> 48:18.226
All the dusty cases.

48:18.227 --> 48:20.806
Give them a glance.
They repay the effort.

48:20.970 --> 48:22.009
Good day to you.

48:22.217 --> 48:23.257
Good day.

48:24.237 --> 48:25.257
Good day.

48:29.297 --> 48:31.137
(INHALES DEEPLY)

48:44.267 --> 48:46.147
(EXHALES)

49:14.237 --> 49:18.256
VANESSA: <i>October the 6th, 1892.</i>

49:18.257 --> 49:20.356
<i>My dear Sir Malcolm,</i>

49:20.357 --> 49:22.256
<i>where this letter shall find you,</i>

49:22.257 --> 49:23.247
<i>I don't know.</i>

49:24.157 --> 49:26.317
<i>I hope, on some far-flung adventure.</i>

49:28.217 --> 49:31.326
<i>I don't want this to
cause you any alarm,</i>

49:31.327 --> 49:35.236
<i>but I've not been entirely
honest in my previous letters.</i>

49:35.237 --> 49:37.207
<i>I didn't want to worry you.</i>

49:37.357 --> 49:40.166
<i>Or perhaps I have lived
too long with secrets</i>

49:40.167 --> 49:42.277
<i>and have become over reliant on them.</i>

49:44.327 --> 49:47.156
<i>All has not gone well with me here.</i>

49:47.157 --> 49:48.226
(SIGHS)

49:48.227 --> 49:51.357
<i>I've been low and sedentary,
unwilling to go outside.</i>

49:53.157 --> 49:56.316
<i>Sunk into a kind of unhealthy lethargy,</i>

49:56.317 --> 50:00.327
<i>sunk into something like my own sadness.</i>

50:04.357 --> 50:06.297
<i>I haven't heard from Mr. Chandler.</i>

50:07.167 --> 50:10.297
<i>He has quite disappeared
from our lives, I think.</i>

50:11.227 --> 50:15.207
<i>I feel his absence keenly...
it's a cutting void.</i>

50:15.367 --> 50:17.316
<i>If I believed in the old words,</i>

50:17.317 --> 50:19.336
<i>I would pray for him.</i>

50:19.337 --> 50:21.267
<i>But that's gone for me now.</i>

50:25.347 --> 50:29.137
<i>Perhaps that is the root of
what has been troubling me.</i>

50:29.317 --> 50:31.176
<i>I have left my faith.</i>

50:31.177 --> 50:32.236
(INHALES DEEPLY)

50:32.237 --> 50:34.246
<i>Or it has left me.</i>

50:34.247 --> 50:36.196
<i>Thus, my prospects seemed</i>

50:36.197 --> 50:39.177
<i>only a long, dark
corridor without an end.</i>

50:40.137 --> 50:42.196
<i>I have done things in
my life for reasons</i>

50:42.197 --> 50:44.256
<i>that seemed right and even moral</i>

50:44.257 --> 50:46.227
<i>in their violent immorality.</i>

50:48.137 --> 50:50.166
<i>And now I stand without that God</i>

50:50.167 --> 50:52.227
<i>upon whom I have always depended.</i>

50:56.137 --> 50:58.216
<i>But please do not fear for me.</i>

50:58.217 --> 51:00.216
<i>I have no fear myself.</i>

51:00.217 --> 51:02.176
<i>The old monsters are gone.</i>

51:02.177 --> 51:05.346
<i>The old curses have echoed to silence.</i>

51:05.347 --> 51:08.206
<i>And if my immortal soul is lost to me,</i>

51:08.207 --> 51:10.157
<i>something yet remains.</i>

51:11.257 --> 51:13.227
<i>I remain.</i>

51:18.137 --> 51:22.296
<i>So I sign off now with hope,
and, as ever, with love...</i>

51:22.297 --> 51:24.137
<i>Vanessa.</i>

51:28.287 --> 51:29.307
(EXHALES)

51:32.367 --> 51:34.187
<i>Post Script.</i>

51:34.307 --> 51:37.206
<i>I don't know if you've
ready access to news,</i>

51:37.207 --> 51:40.256
<i>but we learned today
that Tennyson has died.</i>

51:40.257 --> 51:42.296
<i>The bells are still tolling.</i>

51:42.297 --> 51:45.146
<i>All the flags are at half-mast,</i>

51:45.147 --> 51:47.237
<i>and there are wreathes and
funeral bands everywhere.</i>

51:47.357 --> 51:50.157
<i>London has gone into mourning.</i>

51:51.237 --> 51:53.187
<i>It's a city of tears.</i>

52:01.147 --> 52:05.366
"Beat, happy stars,
timing with things below;

52:05.367 --> 52:08.256
Beat with my heart

52:08.257 --> 52:11.216
more blessed than heart can tell;

52:11.217 --> 52:16.236
Blessed, but for some
dark undercurrent of woe;

52:16.237 --> 52:21.237
That seems to draw, but
it shall not be so:

52:23.167 --> 52:27.157
Let all be well, be well."

